nducted by Freud and Breuer, culminating in the publication of \"\"Studies on Hysteria\"\" in 1895, which laid the foundation for psychoanalytic theory\",1\r\n660,FEDERN,\"Paul Federn was a psychoanalyst and early follower of Freud, known for his contributions to ego psychology\",1\r\n662,RIE,Wilhelm Rie was a psychoanalyst and early member of Freud's circle in Vienna,1\r\n663,EITINGON,\"Max Eitingon was a prominent psychoanalyst and one of Sigmund Freud's early followers, playing a significant role in the early development of psychoanalysis. He was instrumental in the establishment of psychoanalytic societies and journals, contributing to the formalization and dissemination of psychoanalytic theory and practice. Additionally, Eitingon was known for his efforts in founding psychoanalytic training institutes, which helped standardize and professionalize the training of future psychoanalysts. His work left a lasting impact on the field, solidifying his legacy as a key figure in the history of psychoanalysis.\",1\r\n664,BINSWANGER,\"Ludwig Binswanger was a prominent psychiatrist and psychoanalyst who played a significant role in the early psychoanalytic movement. He was deeply influenced by Sigmund Freud's work and contributed to the spread of psychoanalytic ideas. Binswanger is particularly known for developing existential analysis, a therapeutic approach that integrates existential philosophy with psychoanalytic principles. His work bridged the gap between psychiatry and existential thought, making him a key figure in both fields.\",1\r\n665,ABRAHAM,\"Karl Abraham was a prominent psychoanalyst and a key figure in the early psychoanalytic movement. He was an early collaborator of Sigmund Freud and made significant contributions to the development of psychoanalytic theory. Abraham is particularly known for his work on psychosexual development and the theory of libido, which have had a lasting impact on the field of psychoanalysis. His research and insights helped shape the understanding of human psychology and the dynamics of the unconscious mind.\",1\r\n666,BRILL,\"Abraham Arden Brill was a prominent psychoanalyst who played a pivotal role in introducing and popularizing Sigmund Freud's theories in the United States. He is particularly noted for translating many of Freud's seminal works into English, making them accessible to a broader American audience. Through his efforts, Brill significantly contributed to the dissemination and understanding of psychoanalytic thought in the U.S., establishing himself as a key figure in the field of psychoanalysis.\",1\r\n667,JONES,\"Ernest Jones was a prominent psychoanalyst and a key figure in the early psychoanalytic movement. He is best known for his role as a biographer of Sigmund Freud and for his efforts in spreading psychoanalysis in the English-speaking world. Jones played a significant part in establishing psychoanalytic societies and journals, contributing to the growth and institutionalization of the field. His work and influence were instrumental in shaping the development and dissemination of psychoanalytic theory and practice during his time.\",1\r\n677,FREUDIAN PSYCHOANALYSIS,,1\r\n672,SELF-ANALYSIS,\"Self-Analysis is a therapeutic approach that maintains the classic form of psychoanalysis but focuses on analyzing the ego's adaptive functions.\"\"\",1\r\n673,NEO-FREUDIAN PSYCHOANALYSIS,\"Neo-Freudian Psychoanalysis includes modified and more active therapeutic techniques developed by psychoanalysts like Horney, Sullivan, Rank, Jung, and Adler, who diverged from Freud's original theories.\"\"\",5\r\n668,HORNEY,\"Horney was a psychoanalyst who developed her own approach to psychoanalysis, emphasizing the role of social and cultural factors in personality development and neurosis.\"\"\",2\r\n669,SULLIVAN,\"Sullivan was a psychoanalyst who focused on interpersonal relationships and their impact on mental health, contributing to the development of interpersonal psychoanalysis.\"\"\"